08363nam a22011175i 9783110637526DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021944638  a97831106375267 a10.1515/97831106375262doi  a(DE-B1597)507621  a(OCoLC)1290483899  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aND2920b.I435 2022 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a745.6/7090222300aIlluminating Metalwork :bMetal, Object, and Image in Medieval Manuscripts /ced. by Joseph Salvatore Ackley, Shannon L. Wearing. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (XIII, 510 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSense, Matter, and Medium : New Approaches to Medieval Literary and Material Culture ,x2367-0290 ;v400tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tContributors -- tAbbreviations -- tI Introduction -- tPreciousness on Parchment: Materiality, Pictoriality, and -- t the Decorated Book -- tII Technique -- tSurface Effect and Substance: Precious Metals in -- t Illuminated Manuscripts -- tIII Representation -- tMetal Labor, Material Conversions: Goldsmiths in the Life of St. Denis and in Parisian Life, ca. 1300 -- tCopying, Imitation, and Intermediality in Illuminated Ethiopic Manuscripts from the Early Solomonic Period -- tThe Colors of Metalworks: The Painted Materials of Machinery in Byzantium -- tIV Material Translations -- tMetal, Materiality, and Maṣāḥif: Ornamentation in Abbasid Qur’ans -- tManuscript as Metalwork: Haptic Vision in Early Carolingian Gospel Books -- tA “Multimedia” Manuscript: Metalwork and the Siegburg Lectionary -- tIlluminating Luxury: The Gray-Gold Flemish Grisailles -- tV Treasuries in Books, Books as Treasuries -- tThe Golden Spaces of the Uta Codex -- tThe Matter of Memory: Illuminated Metalwork in the Vita of St. Albinus of Angers -- tPackaging the Sainte-Chapelle Relic Treasury, Paris ca. 1500 -- tVI Phenomenology and Piety -- tPilgrimage across Borders: Painted Pilgrim’s Badges in Flemish Illuminated Manuscripts -- tPeripheral Primacy: Metallic Illumination and Material Illusion in the Aussem Hours -- tA Curator’s Note: The Tarnished Reception of Remarkable Manuscripts -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Manuscripts -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Places -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe presence of gold, silver, and other metals is a hallmark of decorated manuscripts, the very characteristic that makes them “illuminated.” Medieval artists often used metal pigment and leaf to depict metal objects both real and imagined, such as chalices, crosses, tableware, and even idols; the luminosity of these representations contrasted pointedly with the surrounding paints, enriching the page and dazzling the viewer. To elucidate this key artistic tradition, this volume represents the first in-depth scholarly assessment of the depiction of precious-metal objects in manuscripts and the media used to conjure them. From Paris to the Abbasid caliphate, and from Ethiopia to Bruges, the case studies gathered here forge novel approaches to the materiality and pictoriality of illumination. In exploring the semiotic, material, iconographic, and technical dimensions of these manuscripts, the authors reveal the canny ways in which painters generated metallic presence on the page. Illuminating Metalwork is a landmark contribution to the study of the medieval book and its visual and embodied reception, and is poised to be a staple of research in art history and manuscript studies, accessible to undergraduates and specialists alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aIllumination of books and manuscriptsxTechnique. 0aIllumination of books and manuscripts, Mediev